demet of God. Moses builded a move
able Churche, and afterward the most
wise king Solomon founded a stan
ding Church not without great cost,
notwithstanding we must not thinke
therfore that God liketh of such great

dwell in suche manner of houses, but because the congregation and people of GOD meet together in those hou ses, to worship and performe due ho nour unto God, to heare the worde of God, to receive the Lords sacraments, and to pray for the assistance and pre sence of God. Churches therefor are very necessary for the Church & people of God. Touching holy assemblies, I have said somewhat in the disputati ons of prayer And although that at the comman demet of God. Moses builded a move able Churche, and afterward the most wise king Solomon founded a stan ding Church not without great cost, notwithstanding we must not thinke therfore that God liketh of such great chareges after that he had sent Christ, and fulsilled the figures. For as before the law was made, it is not to be fosid that the Patriarches did ever bvild a ny Minsters and great Churches, e ven so after the disanulling of the law in the Church of Christ, a meane and sparing cleanlines pleaseth God best, For God misliketh that foolish & mad kinde of buildinges, not much unlike to that unwise building of Babylon, enter prising to set up the toppe of the tower above the cloudes. For God li keth not the riotousnesse of Churches, who without all riot doth gather his church together from out all the parts of the worlde, which Church also hee hath taught both sparingnesse and the contempt of al riot. A Church is large and bigge enough, it it be sufficient to receive al that belong unto it. For the place is provided for men and not for God. But above all thinges let that place be cleane and holy. A Church is hallowed or consecrated, not (as some doe supeestitiously thinke) with the re hearsing of certeyne wordes or ma
king signes and Characters, or with
oyle, or purging fire, but with the wil
of God and his commandement, bid
ding us to assemhle and come together,
promising his presence amongst us : &
also, it is allowed by the holy use of it,
For in the temple the holy Churche of
God is gathered together:the true and
most blessed word of God is also decla
red in the temple: the holy sacramets
of God are received in the temple: and
also in the temple prayers are powred
foorth to God which are most accepta
ble unto him
Verily the place of it selfe is no
thing holy, but because these holye
things are done in that place in respect
that they are done there, the place it
selfe is called holy. Therefore not with
out great cause ought all prophanati
on and filthines be farre from the holy
temple of the Lorde. The Senatours
court or seat of judgemet is accounted
so holy a thing, that whosoever either
in word or deedeused himselfe unreve
rently towardes it, should be accused
of treason. And yet in this court the
Senators onely are gathered and as
semhled together, to heare the matters
of suiters in thinges transitory that
shall passe away and perish. By how
much the more then ought reverence
to bee given unto temples, into the
which the children of God doe come to
woorship him, to heare the true word
of God, and to receive his holy sacra
ments: And therefore as we hate and
abandon all superstition in temples,
so we love not the prophanation of
them, yea rather I say wee can not
abide it. Neither have wee leysure at
this time about the consideration of
temples to rehearse and search out of
pen and plaine superstitios. Of which
matter wee have spoken in another
place,
